It's the big paradox: people always complained about having to mod Oblivion to make it good, but Oblivion at least had a solid foundation to build on. Gameplay mods way outnumber quest mods (at least quality ones do), and good gameplay mods can make up for a lot of the shortcomings the game have. Skyrim, meanwhile, would need a quest overhaul, which just isn't going to happen. Between writing and voice work, the best you can hope for is smaller stuff (companion mods, minor quest lines, etc.) that just won't be enough to make the game worth playing for any extended period of time

Don't buy another version of Skyrim. Pick up Oblivion on a sale, mod it up the ass, and you'll have a much better experience. Then just wait for other people to post Skyrim screenshots and you'll have the best of both world

Morrowind is from a different age, and the start is kind of slow I guess. But I think that's one of the things that exemplifies why I like it so much. There's no bombastic fanfare, and instead you're just vomited out into a shitty village in a colonial possession full of weird, xenophobic assholes. And you suck. You're just another nobody who gets dabbed on by bandits and wildlife. You just build all these little victories on top of each other until you're a demigod who can smack around other demigods without breaking a sweat. Where Oblivion and Skyrim always make you feel the same, Morrowind makes your growth very palpable.
